/PL737/XXREADINGS: SHABBAT/XX/PR

/KAWellfleet Sabbath/XX/PR

The hawk eye of the sun slowly shuts./PR

The breast of the bay is softly feathered/PR

dove grey. The sky is barred like the sand/PR

when the tide trickles out./PR

/PR

The great doors of the Sabbath are swinging/PR

open over the ocean, loosing the moon/PR

floating up slow distorted vast, a copper/PR

balloon just sailing free./PR

/PR

The wind slides over the waves, patting/PR

them with its giant hand, and the sea/PR

stretches its muscles in the deep,/PR

purrs and rolls over./PR

/PR

The sweet beeswax candles flicker/PR

and sigh, standing between the phlox/PR

and the roast chicken. The wine shines/PR

its red lantern of joy./PR

/PR

Here on this piney sandspit, the Shekhinah/PR

comes on the short strong wings of the seaside/PR

sparrow raising her song and bringing/PR

down the fresh clean night./PR

Marge Piercy/XX/PR

/PR

We know what to do with space but do not know what to do
about time, except to make it subservient to space, or to while
it away, to /ITkill time/XX. However, /ITtime is life/XX, and to kill time is to
murder. Most of us seem to labor for the sake of things of space.
As a result we suffer from a deeply rooted dread of time and
stand aghast when compelled to look into its face. Shrinking
from facing time, we escape for shelter to things of space./PI/PR

/PR

/PR

/PR

/PGREADINGS: SHABBAT/XX738/XX/PR

Most of us do not live in time but run away from it; we do not
see its face, but its make-up. The past is either forgotten or
preserved as a cliche¶, and the present moment is either bartered
for a silly trinket or beclouded by false anticipations. The present
moment is a zero, and so is the next moment, and a vast stretch
of life turns out to be a series of zeros, with no real number in
front./PR

/PR

Blind to the marvel of the present moment, we live with
memories of moments missed, in anxiety about an emptiness
that lies ahead. We are unprepared when the problem strikes us
in unmitigated form./PR

/PR

Time is our most important frontier, the advance region of
significant being, a region where our true freedom lies. Space
divides us, time unites us. We wage wars over things of space;
the treasures of time lie open to every one of us./PR

/PR

Time has independent ultimate significance; it is of more
majesty and more evocative of awe than even a sky studded with
stars. Gliding gently in the most ancient of all splendors, it tells
so much more than space can say in its broken language of
things, playing symphonies upon the instruments of isolated
beings, unlocking the earth and making it happen. Time is the
process of creation, and things of space are results of creation.
When looking at space we see the products of creation; when
intuiting time we hear the process of creation. Things of space
exhibit a deceptive independence. They show off a veneer of
limited permanence. Things created conceal the Creator. It is
the dimension of time wherein we meet God, wherein we
become aware that every instant is an act of creation, a
Beginning, opening up new roads for ultimate realizations. /ITTime
is the presence of God in the world of space/XX, and it is within time
that we are able to sense the unity of all beings./PR

Abraham Joshua Heschel/XX/PR

